04673nam a22008895i 9781442624153DE-B159720190516114113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190516s2016    onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426241537 a10.3138/97814426241532doi  a(DE-B1597)465840  a(OCoLC)1044383464  a(OCoLC)922926134  a(OCoLC)952807414  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aBR754.A33 7aLIT0000002bisacsh 7aLIT0041202bisacsh 7aLIT0110002bisacsh04a942.01/72231 aStephenson, Rebecca, eauthor.14aThe Politics of Language :bByrhtferth, Aelfric, and the Multilingual Identity of the Benedictine Reform /cRebecca Stephenson. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2016] 4c©2015  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aToronto Anglo-Saxon Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Literary Context of the Monastic Reform -- tPart One -- tPart Two -- tBibliography -- tIndex  aOld English literature thrived in late tenth-century England. Its success was the result of a concerted effort by the leaders of the Benedictine Reform movement to encourage both widespread literacy and a simple literary style. The manuscripts written in this era are the source for the majority of the Old English literature that survives today, including literary classics such as Beowulf. Yet the same monks who copied and compiled these important Old English texts themselves wrote in a rarified Latin, full of esoteric vocabulary and convoluted syntax and almost incomprehensible even to the well-educated.Comparing works by the two most prolific authors of the era, Byrhtferth of Ramsey and Ælfric of Eynsham, Rebecca Stephenson explains the politics that encouraged the simultaneous development of a simple English style and an esoteric Latin style. By examining developments in Old English and Anglo-Latin side by side, The Politics of Language opens up a valuable new perspective on the Benedictine Reform and literacy in the late Anglo-Saxon period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 16. Mai 2019) 0aLanguages in contactzEnglandzWinchesterxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aLiteracyzEnglandxHistoryyTo 1500. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2015z9783110438673oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066769108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Pilot 2014-2015z978311060681208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Pilot 2014-2019z978311065878108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook Package 2014-2015z978311049093040uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/9781442624153423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442624153.jpg  a978-3-11-049093-0  University of Toronto Press eBook Package 2014-2015  a978-3-11-060681-2  University of Toronto Press Pilot 2014-2015  a978-3-11-065878-1  University of Toronto Press Pilot 2014-2019b2019  a978-3-11-066769-1  UTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aZDB-23-DGGb2015  aZDB-23-DKUb2015